{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Counselman v. Hitchcock |ArgueDateA=December 9 |ArgueDateB=10 |ArgueYear=1891 |DecideDate=January 11 |DecideYear=1892 |FullName=Counselman v. Hitchcock |USVol=142 |USPage=547 |ParallelCitations=12 S. Ct. 195; 35 [[L. Ed.]] 1110; 1892 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 1990; 3 A.F.T.R. (P-H) 2529 |Prior=Appeal from the [[Circuit Court of the United States for the Northern District of Illinois]] |Subsequent= |Holding= |SCOTUS=1891-1892 |Majority=Blatchford |JoinMajority=''unanimous'' |LawsApplied= }}
'''''Counselman v. Hitchcock''''', 142 U.S. 547 (1892), is a [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case in which the Court ruled that not incriminating an individual for testimony was not the same as not requiring them to testify at all. The court reasoned that as long as evidence arising from the compelled testimony could incriminate the individual in any way, the [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] guarantee against self-incrimination was not satisfied. The court then passed the broader "transactional immunity" statute.<ref>{{cite book|author1=William Cohen|author2= John Kaplan|title=Constitutional law: civil liberty and individual rights|year=1981|publisher=Foundation Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8EG5AAAAIAAJ&q=constitutional+law+civil+liberty+and+individual+rights&dq=constitutional+law+civil+liberty+and+individual+rights}}</ref><ref>{{ussc|name=Counselman v. Hitchcock|volume=142|page=547|pin=|year=1892}}.</ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
==External links== * {{caselaw source | case = ''Counselman v. Hitchcock'', {{ussc|142|547|1892|el=no}} | courtlistener =https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/93234/counselman-v-hitchcock/ | findlaw = https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-supreme-court/142/547.html | googlescholar = https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=8370761441591025818 | justia =https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/142/547/ | loc =http://cdn.loc.gov/service/ll/usrep/usrep142/usrep142547/usrep142547.pdf }}
