{{mergeto|Symbolic ethnicity|date=October 2018}}
'''Ethnic option''' is a term coined by sociologist [[Mary C. Waters]]  to express her conception that ethnic identity of the descendants of immigrants is flexible, symbolic and voluntary, not a definitive aspect of their identity.<ref>{{cite book |last=Omi |first=Michael |chapter=Racial Identity and the State |editor-last=Adams |editor-first=Maurianne |title=Readings for Diversity and Social Justice |location=London |publisher=Routledge |year=2000 |page=73–78 [p. 78] |isbn=0-415-92633-5 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=xltVgiCSFaUC&pg=PA78 |via=[[Google Books]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Kleg |first=Milton |title=Hate, Prejudice, and Racism |location=Albany |publisher=SUNY Press |year=1993 |pages=43–44 |isbn=0-7914-1535-X }}</ref> Waters argues that with the achievement of middle-class suburban status, ethnicity becomes a lifestyle option, a costless form of community.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hickman |first=Mary J. |chapter=Migration and Diaspora |editor-last=Cleary |editor-first=Joseph N. |editor2-first=Claire |editor2-last=Connolly |title=The Cambridge Companion to Modern Irish Culture |location= |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2005 |page=131 |isbn=0-521-82009-X }}</ref>

