{{Orphan|date=September 2015}}
{{Infobox court case | name = Garratt v Ikeda | court = [[Court of Appeal of New Zealand]] | date_filed = | image = Coat of arms of New Zealand.svg | date decided = 13 September 2001 | full name = CLIVE CHARLES GARRATT Appellant v KOZO IKEDA Respondent | citations = [2002] 1 NZLR 577| judges = [[Andrew Tipping|Tipping]], [[Peter Blanchard|Blanchard J]], [[John McGrath (judge)|McGrath J]] | prior actions = | subsequent actions = | opinions = | transcripts = [http://www.nzlii.org/cgi-bin/sinodisp/nz/cases/NZCA/2001/316.html Court of Appeal judgment] | Keywords = }} '''Garratt v Ikeda''' [2002] 1 NZLR 577 is a cited case in New Zealand regarding where a contract is cancelled under the Contractual Remedies Act 1979, if the deposit has not been paid, it is still payable, despite section 8(3)(a). <ref name="Chetwin, Graw, Tiong">{{cite book |title=An introduction to the Law of Contract in New Zealand |edition=4th |last1=Chetwin |first1=Maree |last2=Graw |first2=Stephen |last3=Tiong |first3=Raymond |publisher=Thomson Brookers |ISBN=0-86472-555-8 |year=2006 |page=425}}</ref><ref name="Walker">{{cite book |title=Butterworths Student Companion Contract |edition=4th |last1=Walker |first1=Campbell |publisher=LexisNexis |ISBN=0-408-71770-X|year=2004 |page=209-210}}</ref>
==Background== Garratt agreed to purchase Ikeda's property for $1.83 million, with a 10% deposit, payable in 3 instalments.
After paying the first two instalments totaling $50,000, Garratt defaulted on the final $130,000 payment due on the deposit. As a result, Ikeda cancelled the sale, and resold the property to another party for $400,000 more than Garratt had agreed to purchase the property.
With the sale now cancelled, Garratt requested Ikeda to refund the $50,000 he had paid on the deposit. Ikeda refused, despite the fact that he had resold the property for a $400,000 profit.
Garratt eventually sued for his deposit back.
==Held== The court ruled that section 8(3)(a) did not apply here, as the deposit was a performed obligation at the date of the cancellation. Relief under section 9 for the $400,0000 resale profit, was also refused.
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Court of Appeal of New Zealand cases]] [[Category:New Zealand contract case law]] [[Category:2001 in case law]] [[Category:2001 in New Zealand law]]
{{NewZealand-case-law-stub}}

A '''liability waiver''' is a [[Legal instrument|legal document]] that a person who participates in an activity may sign to acknowledge the [[risk]]s involved in his or her participation. By doing so, the company attempts to remove [[legal liability]] from the [[business]] or [[person]] responsible for the activity. The [[Unenforceable|enforceability]] of such a [[waiver]] depends on [[state law]], a [[jury]], and the language of the waiver.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.forc.org/Public/Journals/2005/VOL_16_Fall_2005_Edition.aspx |last=Low |first=Michael J. |year=2005|volume=16|number=3 |title=It's the end of the world as we know it ... and I feel fine: The new rules for drafting liability waivers in Arizona |accessdate=June 27, 2011 |work=''forc.org'' |publisher=Federation of Regulatory Counsel, Inc}}</ref> Liability waivers include pre-accident [[Legal release|releases]] and [[model release]]s (for pictures). Reckless or intentional actions can never be disclaimed and liability resulting from a faulty product cannot be waived.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sports-injury-lawyer.com/PracticeAreas/Attacking-Waiver-of-Liability.asp |title=Liability Waivers – Busting Some Common Myths | accessdate=May 29, 2012}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Unconscionability]]
